R1:
1. I don't find having humanoid robots very appropriate, esp. not in a house, so my ratings have been somewhat lowered by about 0.5-1 points because the robot in the picture looks humanoid.
2. Already existing vacuum cleaning robots I guess make this a slightly more appropriate activity than the others, but even so, not very appropriate as I would use the robotic vacuum cleaner mainly when there are no people around.
3. There are a few social aspects for which I don't see robots as very socially appropriate for carrying things around: I wouldn't want the things around me to move without my knowledge - hence the "very inappropriate" rating for carrying big objects. Cleaning/picking up stuff feels more like it's doing something I'd need to do, which also doesn't have a social aspect to it, so if it was picking up empty glasses, that would be better than picking up a book I started reading and left behind in a specific place. Bringing things, such as food or a glass of water feels less appropriate as it suggests that I can't do it myself - I actually like the excuse of getting up and getting some water or a nibble. I also feel like there's a social component to bringing/giving someone something, esp. food/drinks wise (saying thank you, appreciating the effort), that a robot doing it would be inappropriate.
R2: It seems to me that any action the robot may do is going to be distracting to the family. It seems like they'd like to relax and maybe talk to each other, and the robot doing things at the same time would be interrupting.
R3:
There seem to be many people within the circle, so any cleaning action (vaccum/mopping) and carrying things around seems like it's going to be distracting to the people.

I can imagine the people gather around the robot if it's serving drinks or cold bites, so if it was doing that, it would be fairly appropriate.

Warm food not very suitable for eating standing up.
R4: People might be dancing, don't want to distract them with anything. Might be ok carrying cold nibbles/drinks, but standing in place and having people come to the robot, in which case not sure how that's different to being a table!
R5:
Walking towards someone while cleaning (vaccuming/mopping) or carrying things can be a bit frightening for the person - people tend to walk around each other.

I'd also find it very inappropriate for a robot to start a conversation with me.
R6:
Lots of people around, wouldn't want the robot to distract them.

The robot seems to be heading for the wall - doesn't feel very appropriate for the robot to start a conversation with the wall!
R7: As before, too many people around to do any of the cleaning/carrying actions. I think I can generalise and say I don't find it socially appropriate for a robot to start a conversation with people.
R8:
Same as before - many people in the room, wouldn't want the robot's actions to distract/interrupt them.

I don't think it's socially appropriate for robots to start a conversation.
R9:
Human very close to the robot, can't do any of the cleaning actions.

Maybe the human is heading towards the robot because it's carrying drinks/cold food? In which case that would be fine, but I also don't need a robot to act as a surface for drinks/food...
R10:
Cleaning/carrying actions don't tend to be done when heading straight towards someone, a human would go around, hence I don't think are very appropriate.

I don't think it's socially appropriate for robots to start a conversation.

The robot may be carrying cold food/drinks, and people are around it to help themselves - that seems fine, the robot acts as table of sorts, but it wouldn't be very appropriate for it to move.
R12:

I don't think it's appropriate for the robot to move around with food/drinks - if people need some, they can help themselves.
R13:
Same as before - many people in the room, wouldn't want the robot's cleaning actions to distract/interrupt them.
